in","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Longford and Leitrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEislin</b>, a shortened form of the older <b>Ó hEisleanáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eisleanán</i>’, a byname probably derived from <i>éislinn</i> ‘unsafe, weak’.","English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Alselin</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Anselin</i>, with assimilatory change of <i>n</i> to the following <i>-l-</i>. This is a French form of ancient Germanic <i>Ans(e)helm</i>, composed of the elements <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ and <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet’; compare   Anselm  .","English: topographic name for a dweller ‘(by the) hazel copse’, from Old English <i>hæsling</i>, or a habitational name from any of various minor places called with this word."],"variants":[{"name":"Henslin","meanings":["Irish: possibly a variant of   Heslin  .","South German: from a pet form of   Hensel   (see   Hans  )."]},{"name":"Anselm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Klaus, Heinz.","English and German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Anshelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>ans-</i> ‘god’ + <i>helm</i> ‘protection, helmet’. The personal name was taken to France and England by St. Anselm (<i>c.</i> 1033–1109), known as the Father of Scholasticism. He was born in Aosta, Italy, joined the Benedictine order at Bec in Normandy, France, and in 1093 became archbishop of Canterbury, England."]}]},{"name":"Gerard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gerard de Hesdin was born about 1015, in Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France. He had at least 1 son with Nesta verch Gruffydd. He died about 1065, in Lochaber, Inverness-shire, Scotland, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1015–about 1065":"umbes 1015–umbes 1065","1024–1052":"1024–1052","1038–1098":"1038–1098","1015–1065":"1015–1065","1038":"1038","1015":"1015","1024":"1024","1065":"1065","1098":"1098","about 1015":"umbes 1015","1052":"1052","about 1065":"umbes 1065","Brionne, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Lochaber, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Lochaber, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1015–about 1065":"noin 1015–noin 1065","1024–1052":"1024–1052","1038–1098":"1038–1098","1015–1065":"1015–1065","1038":"1038","1015":"1015","1024":"1024","1065":"1065","1098":"1098","about 1015":"noin 1015","1052":"1052","about 1065":"noin 1065","Brionne, Département de l'Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Brionne, Eure, Normandie, Ranska","Lochaber, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Lochaber, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Ranska","Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Hesdin, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1015–about 1065":"environ 1015–environ 1065","1024–1052":"1024–1052","1038–1098":"1038–1098","1015–1065":"1015–1065","